In Hong Kong, interest rates are at the same level as in the United States.
Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd said the U.S. legislators should immediately reopen negotiations and accept a proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there is a threat that other countries will feel the consequences of this.
The Bloodbath of U.S. Stocks
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected a plan to support the financial system, which would have to be spent $700 billion (almost 12 trillion kroner).
Lawmakers have thus ignored President George W. Bush’s call to support the plan.
Bush said the bill would solve the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
On Monday, U.S. stocks underwent a bloodbath, and leading stock indices recorded the biggest drop in 20 years.
The Dow Jones fell by almost seven percent, with a similar rate of decline last seen in 1987.
The index fell just before the vote, but as it turned out that the proposal was not accepted in the House, the index began to free itself.
