The first virtual service provider will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced and our service providers offer virtually the same services as their Western European partners.
Nevertheless, something is missing for us here - a virtual service provider that forces classic service providers to make significant price cuts.
Maybe it won't be for a long time.
On the website Mobil.cz we have written many times that Czech service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which drew attention to the fact that the price of SMS in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in other EU countries.
As a result of the European Commission's recent move to regulate roaming charges, there may be a conflicting situation - some of the customers of the Czech mobile service providers will receive text messages from abroad cheaper than the domestic ones.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really wants to get into a fight.
This may sound contradictory, as we also have three mobile networks and our penetration is well above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile providers are pleased to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, Chairman of the Board of the Czech Telecommunication Office, has also expressed his opinion on several occasions that there is no place for a new provider in the Czech Republic.
It may be true that a classic service provider with their own network probably no longer has too many chances (however, it would probably be difficult to find frequency).
However, there is another option - the virtual provider.
The entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market brought a significant price reduction, after which the classic service providers had to respond.
In the meantime, even before large fish like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market, sounds similar to ours were heard in the UK.
However, it has been proven that such providers have a place and can be truly successful.
However, for example, we do not have to go too far.
In February this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual service provider Mobilking in Poland.
In less than half a year, this service provider managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth-largest service provider there.
Meanwhile, behind Mobilking is the Penta Financial Group, which in the Czech Republic is also the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual service providers is the ability to focus on a much narrower target group.
In order to operate effectively, you need far fewer customers than a traditional service provider.
This is because it does not involve relatively high construction, mobile network operation and maintenance costs.
Virtual service providers in the world thus usually appear as low-cost - they offer cheap calls and texts, which, however, are often offset by fewer services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the U.K. offers at least fifty percent cheaper text messages than its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it is quite good to bet on a target group as well.
This is because this service is specifically focused on men.
“The real men choose the Mobilking provider – who they like, who they can trust,” says David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, which operates this virtual service.
It is difficult to say whether we can have an idea similar to that of Poland.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD>, spokesman for Vodafone, said: "The Czech market is relatively small compared to the segmental approach on which the majority of virtual service providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively satisfied in terms of the offer of services."
In the Czech Republic, there is no chance, mobile service providers say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual provider in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about the successful expansion of this project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not seem to be very hopeful.
The launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries of our region," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, spokeswoman for the Penta Finance Group, told Mobil.cz in a telephone interview.
Indirectly, it proved that the existing mobile providers in the Czech Republic are not too familiar with this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything in their power to prevent any potential competition from being created.
For some time now, the GTS Novera Group has not been hiding its interest in the launch of a virtual service provider, which aims to take another step towards making Telefonica O2 a real competitor in the field of corporate customers.
“We are very interested in providing not only wired services to our customers, but also mobile telecommunication services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile service providers.
Some of them have already made progress in the negotiations," said Pavel Kaidl, spokesman for the group.
Maybe better times are coming now.
From unofficial information, it seems that we can be lucky for the first virtual service provider by the end of the year.
However, his birth is surrounded by a wall of impenetrable silence.
“At the moment, we do not think that a full-fledged virtual service provider would have a place in the Czech market.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very special.
We have not yet been called a single subject that offers a complex and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88>, of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica 02, told Mobil.cz.
The special situation of the Czech market is also referred to by other service providers.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1>, T-Mobile’s spokeswoman for O2, added: “We have not yet noted a single viable and bilaterally beneficial business project on which to build further.”
He added: “In the T-Mobile network by the end of the year, it is unlikely that any virtual service provider will appear.
At this point, there should be a concrete agreement on our table so that we can think about it in such a short period of time.”
Vodafone’s focus is on meeting its own 3G license requirements.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual service providers, primarily in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure sharing.
This is what we consider to be the most cost-effective for our customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy is to find partners in this area to build networks shared with the fast mobile internet.”
Responsible offices - on a string with service providers
The procedure of mobile providers is easy to understand, and the entry of another provider would lead to an increase in competition, resulting in a decrease in prices and thus a decrease in their profits.
So why should we facilitate the entry of such a competition?
When service providers are able to cooperate with something important, they are also witnessing the connection around the birth of the U:fon.
The biggest pressure on <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is likely to have been around the birth of T-Mobile’s U-phone.
This is evidenced by publicly available information on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> website.
But right now, U:phone is a good reason why we should not allow the virtual service provider to enter.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> added: “The environment of competition in the mobile market has recently been hampered by the entry of the fourth mobile service provider to the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player into the market and its services will impose high standards."
However, in view of this attitude of mobile providers, it is quite astonishing that the Czech regulators are completely disinterested.
In the meantime, it is not just about the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which unfortunately - unlike the UK and other developed countries - does not have the right to intervene in economic competition.
Only the Economic Competitiveness Office is entitled to do so.
But the office is characteristically related to the whole problem.
"The entry of the virtual service provider into the mobile market would only be possible after the conclusion of the contract between the mobile service provider and the virtual service provider for the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential stakeholders is likely not of adequate interest to traditional service providers," Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chlapua, of the Foreign Relations Department of the Economic Competition Office, said in reply to our question.
A statement made by the representatives of the service providers in this way would probably not surprise anyone.
However, from the office, which should represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, ensure that no one can live back to the market situation, this is more than strange.
Especially if Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: “In the country where virtual service providers generally operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to the fall in the price of mobile services.”
However, it is likely that the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS do not concern the correct functioning of the market environment and the pressure to reduce prices.
In this case, it is truly shocking that the reaction of the three mobile service providers reveals quite striking consistency.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is almost self-evident.
As with the filling stations, the exact same gas stations are certainly only the works of random and hard competition.
"The Office has not discovered the signs of anticompetitive proceedings in this case, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
Neither service provider has a leading position, i.e. no proportionately greater responsibility for its market events.
The tools needed to open up the mobile market for virtual service providers are likely to be missing from the telecommunications regulator as well," Chalupa said.
The presentation of the market-leading situation is one of the many points of contention.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, on the basis of which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
After such a market, of course, no Czech service provider is in a leading position.
However, some legal experts also offer a different approach - the creation of a virtual service provider always requires the approval of the network operator.
And the mobile service provider - relatively logically - has a monopoly on its own network.
So, in a certain segment, it is necessarily dominant.
But even if we do not accept this argument, it should be a minimum incentive for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS to have three mobile providers do the same.
In the meantime, complaints from a number of interested parties (including the above-mentioned GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles during their negotiations with all service providers.
Removing responsibility for <0xC4><0x8C>TU is a relatively common trick in telecommunications, with which <0xC3><0x9A>OHS takes its hand off the whole case.
We have seen this in a number of similar situations.
Unfortunately, in the text of the recently adopted Telecommunications Act, the extension of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>’s competence in the field of economic competition in telecommunications was not achieved, although many experts hoped that this would improve the situation.
The <0xC3><0x9A>OHS representatives need to know this well, but probably their interests are different.
It works when no one is listening.
In the meantime, the operation of some kind of virtual service providers, many of which already operate in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that issue their own mobile phone service price lists, which, however, are only partially public.
We are talking about multi-level marketing companies.
Thus, for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the selected ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts against the provider as a classic corporate customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a leading customer, you will receive special offers (and other discounts) afterwards.
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all mobile service providers in the Czech Republic prohibit similar prepayment.
"If there were cases that he was talking about, it could be a breach of terms of contract that we would deal with and that could lead to the termination of cooperation with the company," Martina Kemrova replied to our question on this issue.
But it is quite unlikely that the news of such activity would not have reached the responsible people of the mobile service providers.
First of all, in the case of the three mentioned companies, it can be thousands of customers.
In the meantime, no provider defends itself against such proceedings.
In fact, these companies do not have negligible profits from their activities, and in the meantime, unlike real virtual service providers, they are not particularly threatened with their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns of possible problems: "The law allows for similar speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card is not in their name on their phone, so they cannot have it in full as the general customers of mobile providers."
But at least that’s what the CTU should do.
In addition, another question will be raised for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile service providers are faced with a similar procedure, why are they preventing the creation of a virtual service provider?
It should be added that <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has a relatively strong right to disclose such activities and, if it does not wish, does not have to be satisfied with the explanation by the service providers that they have not suspected such a thing and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we won't be the most expensive
As has been stated several times in the text, the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market has led to a noticeable reduction in the price of services.
In the meantime, in virtually every country where virtual service providers have been established, the classic service providers have been trying to prevent their creation from becoming more or less so.
The arguments they used were practically the same - too small, possibly too satisfied market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, in developed countries, it is at this very moment that regulators intervened, which in no way defended the interests of mobile providers but their customers.
Then, either through formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual service provider, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are advocating the whole thing for each other.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that ambiguous competencies are good for them in these cases.
But let's not give up the fight.
If the background information is good and our virtual provider is really coming out soon, the Czech mobile market may be on the move again.
If one of the providers would allow the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, it would be difficult for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of further interested parties.
And compared to the rest of Europe, we may not be more expensive to call.
