People behave in a similar way, from which some researchers conclude that there are comparable subjective experiences.
But I don't believe in that.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our own subjective experiences to animals.
On the one hand, circuits associated with human consciousness almost always contain the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its role in short-term memory and implementation/control functions).
This vast area is more advanced in man than in other mammals, and seems to be completely lacking in other living beings.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cerebral cortex, for example, the awareness of who we are, or in the case of design and decision-making, it can be reasonably assumed that man is different from even the other major mammals.
Another dramatic feature lies in the linguistic nature of man: Since a significant part of human experience is related to language, it is often claimed that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, the animals can be excluded.
However, even if it did not depend on language, the language would certainly influence it, so animal consciousness, whatever its nature, is likely to be very different from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness may be like for other animals.
If the mind cannot be measured as an internal and subjective thing, and because of the special hardware it cannot be analyzed on the basis of our own experience, then his research presents us with serious problems.
Most of my headlines relate to the content of conscious living, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that is probably more easily accessible to science.
The conscious processes of animals could be examined regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in experiments on the short-term memory of the main animals, especially in the case of visualization.
However, in this assumption also examined by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, they rely more on the neural connections of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: both may be the same or not.
Interestingly, this assumption also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex in the creation of visualization.
What is the result of these emotions?
I attribute this to the fact that an emotional system, like its fear, is activated in the brain that is aware of its own activity.
What we call "fear" is, therefore, the mental state in which we are when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as bodily reactions) occupies working memory.
In this way, the emotions are closely related to the areas of the cerebral cortex that are characteristic of the main mammals and in particular of humans.
With the linguistic character, the perception is divided into subtle degrees, because with the help of words and grammar, we are able to distinguish and categorize states, so that we describe them to others as well as ourselves.
Antonio Damasio, on the other hand, is of the opinion that emotions stem from the simpler activities of the body's sensory areas of the cerebellum and brain stem, as does Jaak Pankseep, who, however, prefers to focus on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it can easily play a role in the overall emotions of the species.
I can't theoretically deny this, but I think it's unproven.
Pankseep believes that what appears to be fear in rats and humans is likely to be felt in both cases: How can one check whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave in the same way?
A cockroach escapes in case of danger, does he also feel fear?
In my opinion, only such behavior is not yet proof of the same experience.
Although the neural comparison continues to help: rats and humans have similar brain stems, but cockroaches do not have brains.
But is the brain stem responsible for emotions?
And even if this could be proven in terms of humans, how could we prove it in terms of rats?
I think rats and other mammals, but maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have feelings.
However, I do not know how to prove this.
And because their emotions are suspected to be fundamentally different from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to research the emotional behavior of rats rather than the emotional emotions.
In any case, progress in this area is at the neural level, if we measure the same in rats and humans.
Just as I don’t research language and consciousness in rats, I don’t research emotions because I don’t know if they exist.
To others, this may seem like a short-sighted attitude, but I'm moving forward rather than constantly colliding with a wall.
