However, in many respects, the city he described and made a tourist attraction – which is also included in the Florida travel guide published by the Federal Writers of the Crisis Project – is distinct from its surroundings.
As independent, dignified and closing as it was in the 1930s, when, according to Hurston's writing, Florida, urban blacks were often unwilling to share their true thoughts with white people who "know so little about us that they don't know what they're talking about."
Even in the year when the black presidential candidate, Barack Obama, encourages an open exchange of ideas on the issue of race, many here are distrustful of the views of outsiders.
