"You have to tell me."
Eatonville has long been characterized by a paradox of victory and struggle.
At the same time, it is a historically significant model of the black population, but at the same time it is a community of nearly 2,400 people where poverty rates reach double the national average.
Partly a literary node, and partly an example of American slavery, sometimes looked down, sometimes for praise, on a southern, urban, black culture that flourished in the shadow of oak trees.
It’s no surprise, then, that the people here are both proud and defenders.
The image of Eatonville has been important since Zora (here everyone calls Hurston).
In books written in an honest, strong dialect - such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937) - he introduced his hometown to the world.
The five paragraphs of the Florida Travel Guide have transformed the city, located next to Route 17, from Florida’s long-forgotten center to one of the locations of black history and human drama.
Hurston, who was brave in both life and literature, introduced his readers to Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then looked into the more confidential spheres.
He wrote: “We find a modern public school on the right, with a brown-based white border, carefully maintained courtyards and playgrounds that Howard Miller takes care of, although he can barely write and read.”
She mentioned Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells all kinds of drinks and anything that may be needed in temporary accommodations."
Thus, in a few hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with autonomy, but at the same time with illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
It is clear that Fodor's guidebook presented it differently.
This description really didn’t like everyone.
"She told me things the way they were," said Ella Dinkins, a 90-year-old Johnson girl, who made them immortal by quoting the screaming songs that men sang about their beauty.
He added, "Some people don't like it."
Hurston is still remembered here as the living individual who often visited home after his family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
The 77-year-old Augustus Franklin recalled that when Hurston stormed the city, he usually arrived unannounced in a bustling Chevrolet, smoking cigarettes, and in a city with long sleeves where people still pride themselves on their dignified outfits today.
