“People were always happy to see Zora,” Franklin said.
However, on the terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, he added, hinting in his chair, "He never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, he was poor and his books were not republished.
It seemed that Eatonville, along with most of the world, had forgotten about it.
Although she was once a popular writer, a contemporary of Langston Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in a signless grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she previously lived.
In Eatonville there were no significant memorabilia, or large, public readings.
"I don't think they understood how much he enriched the world or what he left us at all," said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston's 2003 biography, "Wrapped in a Rainbow."
The turning point came in 1980.
Orange County officials wanted to build a five-lane road across the city through the two-lane main road, instead of Kennedy Avenue, which played an important role in community life.
Expanding Orlando has already penetrated the Interstate 4 motorway that connects the states on the western border of the city.
