In the 1950s, the struggles related to racial mixing made the community taste of hatred.
“At that time, a team of white boys came over and threw out those sitting on the side of the road with oranges and other things,” Franklin said.
"There was a woman who died in this.
They threw a Greek woman out of a car.”
In a letter to The Orlando Sentinel in 1955, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's decision to impose violent integration, stating in his "Brown v. Board of Education" ruling: "It violates me rather than you."
Today, residents say that while the school disintegration has been positive in some respects, it has weakened the cohesion of the Eatonvilles and undermined the confidence of young people.
"Black children are used to killing them - I remember that - the man hugged his teacher in the morning and in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins, the executive director of the non-profit organization We Save the Eatonville Community.
"This lasted as long as the students and teachers came from a common place," he added.
“We didn’t hug our white teacher because he was a white teacher — I mean, there were cultural differences between us,” Nathiri said.
However, human rights has helped many others to rise up to Zora Neale Hurston – in black writers, actors, and artists who have risen above prejudices, as she has done, with such overwhelming self-confidence and lines as this: “How can anyone know?
