Boyd put it more simply: "So he saved Eatonville."
The victory over the road construction project helped to change the city’s image of itself.
Increasing numbers of people outside the city appeared, such as lawyer Rachelle Munson, who started going to church in 1993, and locals began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville was added to the National Historic List in 1998.
In 2006, a new, one-storey library (named after Hurston, of course) opened on refurbished and beautified Kennedy Avenue.
Eatonville remains the cucumber of Florida: it’s not just ten miles from downtown Orlando, but sometimes it feels like an out-of-town sidewalk in the summer rain; it’s as small as when 27 black families were founded in the 1880s.
