Those who speak in their dreams
Some kids talk at night.
I don’t mean those who wake up and fully awake to tell what happened to them that day, but those who talk while they sleep.
The phenomenon may seem scary at first, but it is actually completely harmless.
This benign sleep disorder is called somniloquism.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure most of you've been told he spoke at night.
In terms of its frequency, it can be completely rapsodic (for example, only occurs once in a disease with a high fever), or more systematic (daily, weekly or monthly), and usually the next day the child does not remember anything.
Its appearance cannot be traced back to a single cause.
It is often accompanied by other sleep disorders, such as nightmares, nocturnal vomiting, bed-wetting (enuresis nocturna) or sleepwalking, but this is not legal.
As we have already mentioned, it can be accompanied by a state of high fever, or even a stressful situation or an elevated state of excitement.
In any case, little has been studied so far.
The intensity of speech is also very variable.
It may be quiet, calm, it may consist of unrelated words, murmuring, but in contrast to all these, it may also occur in the form of screaming, crying, or longer speech.
If the phenomenon is very intense, it is advisable to observe the child and consult a specialist. The examination can reveal whether there is some problem that causes a lot of anxiety in the background and thus can offer a solution.
As already mentioned, it is a benign phenomenon, therefore, there is no cure for it, unless it is accompanied by some other form of sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, insomnia or a stressful situation).
However, there are a few things we can do, here is a preventive measure:
Make sure that the child stays calm before going to bed.
We choose reassuring toys and avoid the child watching frightening or more aggressive TV shows or series.
For children who are prone to nervousness or who are more difficult to relax, we teach some relaxation methods to help them find inner peace.
This will help the child to sleep more relaxed.
If you start talking while you sleep, let's try to stay calm.
Remember, this is harmless for the child, and the next day they will not remember anything.
Useful Advice
Do not wake the child up.
It would be superfluous, because the child is not aware, but it would come out of sleep.
Despite talking, he actually sleeps longer and rests.
Remember, if multiple times of severe anxiety is accompanied by the phenomenon, it is advisable to consult a specialist or to reveal what causes a high degree of anxiety from the child.
If you speak clearly (this is the rarest case), don’t start asking them to learn anything from them.
It would be superfluous, because while sleeping, you are not so conscious as to gather your thoughts.
On the other hand, you only hear the speech, but you do not see the accompanying dream images, so be careful with the interpretation of what you have heard and the possible conclusions.
Never tell a child that they can question their secrets at night.
It's not even a joke.
That caused a lot of anxiety.
So the most important thing is not to worry, as it’s just a few minutes of harmless episode.
