The blood is safe again.
Yesterday, Héma-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of its founding. President Dr. Francine Décary had a good reason for the celebration because Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood donor companies in the world today.
And most importantly, he managed to regain people’s trust, which was seriously damaged by the infection-related blood scandal of the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well known, the national blood supply, managed by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Service, became infected with acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (HIV) and hepatitis C viruses in the 1980s.
Following the drama and general upheaval, the Government of Canada launched an official investigation in February 1994, led by Judge Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances leading up to the tragedy and to make suggestions for future cases.
While Judge Krever's late report was submitted, some provinces set up their own committees aimed at designing a new blood management system for Canada.
In Québec, the Gélineau Committee carried out this task.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two blood services were established in Canada: one is Héma-Québec, which serves Québec, and the other is the Canadian Blood Supply Society, which is responsible for the supply of all other provinces and territories.
“When Héma-Québec began operations in 1998, only 38% of people had confidence in the Québec blood supply system,” recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was desperate.
"In the years to come, however, we have been able to regain people's trust as a result of improving the safety of blood preparations and our work in the field." Décary proudly declares that by the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the population of Québec had been trusted by Héma.
Dr. Décary, however, does not forget that "confidence is an extremely fragile thing".
Since the establishment of Héma-Québec on September 28, 1998, it has been applying the precautionary principle.
A number of cases have been discovered in Europe during this period when a new variant of the disease Creutzfeldt-Jacob, which has infected people, has also been found - says the doctor, who has been in charge of the company since its inception in 1998.
"We had no idea whether this disease was spreading through blood.
Therefore, we relied on one of the most important recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports. According to this, if we are uncertain about this and there is a risk of developing a serious disease, then we should apply exclusive measures to the cause of this. In this case, it is clear that the cause of this disease is Creutzfeldt-Jakob.
Therefore, in April 1999, we did not accept blood from people who have spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980.
A few years ago, there was no doubt that the disease was spread in the blood.
This case convinced us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle.”
In 1999, a technique was introduced on the market that allows for a much more sensitive diagnosis of the HIV virus. This is a nucleic acid test (NAT), which is able to directly detect the virus in the blood of blood donors, and not antibodies against the virus.
With the help of the NAT test, we were able to shorten the window period, which lasts from the infection until we are able to detect the virus in the blood with our technical means.
This period could be reduced for a period of less than a week.
This significantly mitigated the risk of blood donors infecting the bloodstream beyond their knowledge, as well as not being able to detect it.
With these developments, the risk of AIDS spreading through blood transfusions has been greatly reduced.
Nowadays, the risk of someone getting HIV-infected blood is 12 million to one.
“In a nutshell, this means that we should allocate 12 million blood preparations until someone becomes infected with HIV.
Because Héma-Québec distributes between 400 and 500,000 blood preparations each year, it would take more than 24 years for such a case to occur and someone to become infected with HIV through a blood preparation.
I think that today anyone can accept or prescribe blood transfusions for the purpose of restoring health, says the number one leader of Héma-Québec.
“The challenge of the next decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products.
We never know what kind of new pathogen will enter the system.
In fact, it was only last year that the chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, enters the blood with insect bites.
Therefore, we need to be constantly open," continued Dr. Décary, and then stressed that in addition to the test reserves, Héma-Québec must provide sufficient permanent reserves.
“As the population ages, so do the needs.
Because cancer treatments have become more aggressive, patients often need to replace red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donor population, as the number of people eligible for blood donation in the network accounts for only 3% of the population of Quebec.
However, any healthy person at least 18 years of age who meets the eligibility criteria may donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of applicants do not accept blood because they are infected with AIDS or malaria, and those who have been in a country where malaria kills are not eligible for blood donation for one year.
“With this 3%, we have enough reserves to meet the needs of the hospitals.
It's very rare that we're out of stock.
However, we must increase the number of blood donors to the extent that the existing ones age, because after a while they can no longer donate blood.
But it’s very difficult to convince people to donate blood, but it’s even harder to keep them and get them to become regular blood donors.
In today’s fast-paced world, there is hardly a single hour for a person to go and donate blood,” says Francine Décary.
With a budget of $297 million annually, Héma-Québec provides not only blood preparations, but also human tissues, such as bone transplants, heart keys, eyeballs, and skin tissues, which they use almost exclusively for serious purposes.
These tissues are analyzed, transformed and frozen, and then placed in Héma-Québec, which at the same time manages Quebec’s only public stem cell bank.
The hair can be extracted from the navel cord, which is treated only as medical waste, blood that is rich in stem cells, so it also allows the treatment of serious diseases (such as leukemia).
“We have been celebrating for a few weeks that the 1,000th Nail Corps sample has entered our bank, and we plan to take more than a thousand new samples each year.
We will probably start offering these for organ transplants at the beginning of next year," said Dr. Décary, who said that the navel cord blood-removal program is very popular today.
"Many mothers are saddened that they don't have a chance to do this" - this is true, because Héma-Québec is not in a position to make this complex and expensive program available in every hospital in Quebec.
