The Psychology of Over-Citation: Why Do We Spend More Money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more money, overvalue the goods.
The neuro-economic foundations of this well-known — and seemingly irrational — behavior have been discovered by neurologists and economists at the University of New York.
According to a study published in the journal Science, people don’t want to succumb to a type of competition such as an eBay auction, so they’re more likely to pay too high a price.
The research tried to map the nervous system scheme of this "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers took part in the lottery, while the other group took part in the player auction, while the active brain areas of the experimenters were examined using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method.
In both games, participants were able to win money, but during the auction game - in which an essential element is the over-licensing of the other party - the complex called striatum, under the cerebral cortex, went into intensive operation when the game was lost.
This area of the brain plays a role in the "rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system along with several other functions.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the rise in price can be explained by avoiding the intense reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, the members of the research group of economists also carried out a financial follow-up study.
In this, three groups tendered against one partner under different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the real value of the product in question and they made their bets.
Another group was also promised that if they were to get out of the game, they would be rewarded with another $15 in cash.
The third group, however, received $15 just before the auction, but the members of the group lost that money in the event of a losing auction.
So the difference between the two groups was only so much that for one group the gain was emphasized, for the other group the loss.
However, as evidenced by the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the team playing "against loss" were willing to bet higher than the control and the "force" group.
