Hepatitis: When to see a doctor?
Around half a billion people in the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary, chronic liver disease is one of the leading causes of death.
The number of people infected with hepatitis at home can be up to one hundred thousand, but they only treat seven thousand, which is the reason: patients often do not know that they have been infected.
The name hepatitis is a collector name for infectious liver disease caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, characterized by inflammation of the liver and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases caused are different from each other.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g., contaminated food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body tissues (e.g., vaginal discharge, vaginal discharge).
Travelers should definitely be protected against the A and B viruses, there is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A occur two to three weeks after eating the infected food, generally accompanied by feeling unwell, weakness, abdominal complaints, nausea.
After this, yellowing of the skin and eye whites develops, the stool becomes bright, the urine darkens, the healing can take up to two to three weeks.
Every year, one million people worldwide die from the most severe form of the disease, from liver cancer and hepatic insufficiency caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected people receive drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to liver contractions, liver cancers.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, because the pathogen destroys the liver cells involuntarily, in many cases, the first symptoms only appear after 20-30 years.
Thus, after that, it is very important to carry out early prevention, regular screening tests.
In three groups, there are far more than average such diseases: people who had had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users, and tattooists.
There are currently 200 million people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus in the world.
Since the disease can already be detected by a routine laboratory test, it is worth seeing a doctor if any symptoms of unknown origin are detected.
By recognizing the disease in time, it can be cured, the virus can be expelled from the body, thus eliminating the ability to become infectious and prevent the development of cancer.
September 30th is the World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing patients around the world.
It aims to draw attention to the chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, the causes of their development and the importance of early detection of the disease.
