The flight of the donggo is imitated by the smart car
What would be the best way to develop technologies to avoid collisions if not to imitate the barrier sensors that occur in the world of nature?
For example, bees.
In a surprise project presented at CEATEC in Japan, dong bees gave Nissan engineers the strategic starting point for how to build the next generation of collision-avoiding systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a BR23C-type, bio-engineered autorobot control system, a robotic minicar equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the ultimate goal of helping to develop a system that is capable of all kinds of impacts.
Each bee forms its own oval-shaped personal space during flight, which is actually very similar to our safety casing,” Kazuhhiro Doi, Chief Technology Officer for PR and R&D, explained at the exhibition.
It is important for the complex eye of the uterus, which is able to see at an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions.
In order to replicate the function of the complex eye, the engineers approached the idea of a laser distance meter.
It identifies obstacles within 2 metres of the 180-degree viewing range before BR23C, calculates their distance, and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately transformed into a collision avoidance operation.
During the fraction of a second, the obstacle is detected, and then the car robot mimics the movements of the uterus, immediately shifting the direction of its wheels to the extent necessary to avoid collision.
Unlike any current system, this avoiding maneuver takes place in a completely instinctive manner.
“If this were not the case, the auto-robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the auto-robot project.
You must react in an instinctive and immediate manner, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety pads, a layer within which collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what a bee does in order to avoid other bees.
This process should take place at a glance.
However, unlike bees, the deviation cannot be directed upwards, downwards or transversely, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the endless possibility available to bees to avoid the other bees, only the rotating movement and acceleration and the slowdown were used as the option available to the car robot.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and higher in energy density, which means that they have a longer service life than the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, instinctive intelligent response is important, not the ability to process data, let alone the ability to store it.
This structure only needs to process a few incoming signals per second and respond to them.
You don’t need to keep them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so you’re constantly using just a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
There is no need for gigabytes or megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in the development of instantaneous avoidance technology, which, according to Nissan’s estimate, can be incorporated into mass-produced cars within ten years.
An additional application can be used by integrating the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system to avoid obstacles on the road to drive the car to the specified end destination.
