The energy comes from the waves, and now the big ones come.
An inexhaustible source of energy that accounts for 70 percent of the planet’s surface and is only now discovered by large international energy companies.
Waves, sea currents, lightning bolts, all renewable energy sources that have been spotted by giants like the Chevron, who are now trying to get their hands on.
For hundreds of years now, they've been researching the possibility of how to extract energy from the motions of the sea, and in the 1970s, during the first oil crisis, research was on the rise.
Around 1980, when the price of petroleum fell, the idea of utilising marine energy was dismissed, but today the demands of environmental protection and the re-increase in the price of petroleum are giving the sector a new impetus.
The World Energy Council in London (WEC) estimates that 15 percent of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by facilities that use waves from the seas.
That’s twice the amount that nuclear power plants are currently producing.
In addition, there would still be streams and streams.
The giants are in decline.
Enersis was the first company to commit itself to marine energy and signed an agreement in 2005 on a power plant to be established in northern Portugal.
It seemed like a revolutionary step when the signature was announced.
Two years have passed since then, and more and more companies have voiced their support for marine energy, including those who have been committed to traditional energy so far.
“Chevron is studying technologies that utilise ocean energy and is considering cooperating with us,” said a spokesperson for the Wall Street Journal, one of the U.S. oil giants.
The cooperation in question relates to the acquisition of the licence required to launch the Alaska project for the utilisation of marine energy issued by the U.S. Energy Committee.
This is not a small matter, especially considering the fact that the United States is currently producing oil in Alaska, and President Bush has also recently launched a plan for further drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. in New York and Ocean Power in New Jersey are also on the path of energy from the sea. The amounts invested so far, as far as details can be known, are evidence of increasing interest.
The technology is waiting for development.
Experts say that this is still an initial technology, just because the energy from the sea does not dispel doubts about the environmental impact.
The facilities that currently exist, such as those of Portugal or Scotland, are all small and therefore do not cause too many problems in terms of the ecosystem.
However, in order to be able to produce energy on a larger scale, there is a need for facilities that also have a greater environmental impact.
There are several options available: for example, Ocean Power uses an interconnected boiler system.
The shocks caused by the waves and moving the boobs upwards are converted into hydraulic pressure by the pistons and cylinders placed inside them.
The pressure rotates a turbine, which feeds a generator.
Electrical power is supplied by cables under the sea to land.
At the same time, there are four facilities of a similar nature in the design phase, which are only waiting for federal approval. Some of the energy produced would be used in a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, has already started energy production for a shopping mall and a parking lot with six underwater turbines located in the East River, New York.
When the water moves in a stream, it rotates the blades of the turbines, and this rotational movement feeds the generator.
Verdant has announced that it has a long list of partners who are only waiting for permissions needed to use the energy.
After the waves, it's a stream.
At present, differentiated attention is being paid to the opportunities that can be exploited through the waterway.
Although this is a periodic phenomenon, the trend is more predictable than the wind, the sun, or the waves, so it can be considered a more reliable source of energy.
New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as the rest of the coastal states, spent $7.5 million in 2008, precisely to exploit the energy supplied by the pipeline. This amount is expected to increase to 35 million in 2009.
